com.camerontec.catalys.util.collection

Class FifoFileQueue

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.catalys.util.collection.FifoFileQueue
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IFifoFileQueue

    public class FifoFileQueue
extends Object
implements IFifoFileQueue
    FIFO file queue implementation.

    Each entry in the queue is stored in a separate file.

    Writing an entry on the queue is guaranteed to either succeed completely or fail completely. That is, any entry which is on the queue is guaranteed to be complete.

    Reading and removing an entry from the queue is a 2 step process:

    • get the contents of the first entry from the queue, blocking if necessary
    • remove the first entry once processed.
    In this way the reader my crash while processing the entry without affecting the state of the queue. However, the reader must remember to explicitly remove the entry once processed otherwise the same entry will be returned on the next read.

    File indices are controlled exclusively by the queue writer. Therefore, at initialisation a queue writer must deduce the next index to use based on the contents of the queue directory.

    Queue readers, on the other hand, must not assume any state beyond what is currently in the queue directory. It is possible that a queue writer may die and return at any time, which might result in queue indices being reset (if it so happens the writer starts up and there are no entries in the queue). Readers must cope with this by always examining the state of the queue directory when it transitions from empty to non-empty.

    To make this processing somewhat more efficient a helper class is used to cache all existing queue file names, which potentially saves the reader from calculating the next file to read every time.

    This class is not thread safe.

    Author:
    Maria Ischuk modified to use BytesSegment as part of adapting FlatFileAdapter to use IFIXMessage/IMessageTransformer(StandardFixTransformer)

      • get

        public IFifoFileQueue.Entry get()
                         throws IOException,
                                InterruptedException
        Description copied from interface: IFifoFileQueue
        Get the contents of the first entry on the queue without removing it from the queue.

        This call blocks until an entry is placed on the queue or until it is otherwise interrupted.

        It is the caller's responsibility to call IFifoFileQueue.remove(com.camerontec.catalys.util.collection.IFifoFileQueue.Entry) once the entry is processed in order to remove it from the queue. Failure to do this results on successive calls returning the same bytes.

        The caller may optionally choose to mark the returned entry as read in case there is an error while processing it.

        Specified by:
        get in interface IFifoFileQueue
        Returns:
        The first entry on the queue, or null if the queue is closed or not open for reading.
        Throws:
        IOException - On error with underlying file system.
        InterruptedException - If interrupted before an entry is placed on the queue.
        See Also:
        IFifoFileQueue.markAsRead(com.camerontec.catalys.util.collection.IFifoFileQueue.Entry)

      • markAsRead

        public boolean markAsRead(IFifoFileQueue.Entry entry)
                   throws IOException
        Description copied from interface: IFifoFileQueue
        Mark the specified entry as read.

        Once marked as read, IFifoFileQueue.Entry.isMarkedAsRead() returns true on subsequent calls to IFifoFileQueue.get(). The caller may use this to perform any required duplicate processing checks.

        Implementing subclasses must guarantee to preserve this marked state across restarts.

        Note that entries need not be marked as read; they may still be removed without being in the read state.

        Specified by:
        markAsRead in interface IFifoFileQueue
        Parameters:
        entry - The entry to mark.
        Returns:
        True if successfully marked as read, false otherwise.
        Throws:
        IOException - On error with the underlying file system.
